    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras are positioned for a high-ceiling performance today, anchored by the elite 87.42 score of **Yordan Alvarez**, who draws a favorable matchup against Gil (5.74 xERA). **Yordan Alvarez** serves as our primary offensive engine, benefiting significantly from a +19% SP skill advantage and a clean platoon look. Supporting him is **Junior Caminero**, whose 73.02 projection stands out as our second-strongest play. Despite a minor park penalty, **Junior Caminero** thrives against Woods Richardson due to a favorable spot in the order and a +11% bump derived from the opposing starter's profile. We are also tracking **Luke Raley** (57.49) and **Kazuma Okamoto** (55.60) as solid contributors; **Luke Raley** benefits from a strong platoon advantage against McGreevy, while **Kazuma Okamoto** remains a steady UTIL play against Cecconi.\n\nNavigating today\u2019s roster required a difficult call on **Chase Meidroth**, who finished just outside the starting nine with a 47.41 score. While **Chase Meidroth** offers high-upside utility, the optimizer favored the efficiency of **Caleb Durbin** (49.07), largely due to **Caleb Durbin**\u2019s massive +16% park factor adjustment which outweighed the positional flexibility offered by the bench. On the defensive side of the ledger, we remain cautious regarding **Trea Turner** and **Kyle Schwarber**, both of whom are facing the elite Sale (2.88 xERA). While their raw talent keeps them in the lineup, their scores are dampened by nearly 20% due to the SP skill factor. Additionally, we are monitoring **Hyeseong Kim** (48.57); his status is contingent on a pending lineup, and while he faces a tough southpaw in Shota Imanaga, the +5% wind-out factor provides a glimmer of hope for a power surge if he secures the #8 spot. Given the scarcity of steals in this league, **Victor Scott II** remains a mandatory start for his speed potential, even as he faces a tough hold SP in Hancock.",
